The foundation stack — four layers.

Picture four layers stacked on top of each other, and read them from the bottom up. Each layer is built on the one below.

At the bottom is cloud object storage. This is just bytes on disk — parquet files plus a transaction log directory. It is cheap, durable, and infinitely scalable, but on its own it has no transactional guarantees.

Above that sits delta lake. Delta lake turns those raw files into proper tables. A special log directory holds an ordered sequence of jay-son commit files, and readers compose them to see a consistent snapshot. This is where acid transactions, time travel, schema enforcement, and merge come from.

Next is the engine — spark plus photon. Open-source spark does the planning and distribution, and photon accelerates the hot path. One runtime covers batch, streaming, sequel, and machine learning.

And at the top is unity catalog, the governance layer. Three-level names, grant and revoke, and lineage across everything. The thing to remember is the order — storage, then delta lake, then the engine, then governance. Each one only makes sense because of the layer beneath it.
